0-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','So after finding a wonderful and encouraging resource at the <a title=\"Maternal Wellness Center\" href=\"http://www.maternalwellness.org/\">Maternal Wellness Center</a> Timmy and I are super excited about cloth diapering. Cloth diapering has come a long way from safety pins and cloth (that\'s what my mommy used on me!)\n\nApart from it potentially saving us at least $5000 (that\'s if we cloth diaper two kids... and I\'m not exaggerating with that number) I\'m also excited about what it means for our impact on the environment. Knowing that 600 of my child\'s dirty diapers are sitting in some landfill and will take generations and generations to decompose really bothers me. The number is just too real. I can picture that.','We\'re Cloth Diapering!',0,'','draft','open','open','','','','','2008-08-11 19:28:49','2008-08-11 23:28:49','',0,'http://burningones.com/?p=291',0,'post','',0),(292,2,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'','inherit','open','open','','168-revision','','','2008-08-13 17:25:39','2008-08-13 21:25:39','',168,'http://burningones.com/1999/11/30/168-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(293,2,'2008-08-13 17:32:46','2008-08-13 21:32:46','Research Topics:\nInformation Age, First World Problems\n\nOutline:\nIntroduction\nDefinition of Consumable Media\nTypes and Examples of Consumable Media\nIncorrect Media Associations\nMagazines, Video Rentals, Libraries, Books, Etc.\nConclusion w/ reference to Part 2 of the 3 parter','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'Media that costs nothing, is interesting but not necessary, and comes in large volumes is a first-world problem that has rapidly grown since the introduction of the internet.  I\'m proposing that a good title for this is Consumable Media and needs its own set of triage rules in order to deal with it (if you really want to deal with it at all).','inherit','open','open','','168-revision-2','','','2008-08-13 17:32:46','2008-08-13 21:32:46','',168,'http://burningones.com/2008/08/13/168-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(294,2,'2008-08-13 17:43:28','2008-08-13 21:43:28','Outline:\nIntroduction\n    The effects of the Information Age\n    Generation-Y and Z\n    The attractiveness of information\nDefinition of Consumable Media\n    Consumable media is provided free of charge, interests you but is not required content for you to master, and comes in large volumes.  In addendum, it is more than likely archived \nTypes and Examples of Consumable Media\nIncorrect Media Associations\n    Magazines, Video Rentals, Libraries, Books, Etc.\nConclusion w/ reference to Part 2 of the 3 parter','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'Media that costs nothing, is interesting but not necessary, and comes in large volumes is a first-world problem that has rapidly grown since the introduction of the internet.  I\'m proposing that a good title for this is Consumable Media and needs its own set of triage rules in order to deal with it (if you really want to deal with it at all).','inherit','open','open','','168-revision-3','','','2008-08-13 17:43:28','2008-08-13 21:43:28','',168,'http://burningones.com/2008/08/13/168-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(295,2,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Solution or Problem Based Life Processing',0,'Are you solution based or problem based in your approach to living your life?  What does that even mean?  It turns out that is an important question to ask yourself if you find that you have a significant amount of non-starters in your day to day existence.','draft','open','open','','','','','2008-08-20 13:07:07','2008-08-20 17:07:07','',0,'http://burningones.com/?p=295',0,'post','',0),(296,2,'2008-08-20 13:05:08','2008-08-20 17:05:08','','Solution or Problem Based Life Processing',0,'','inherit','open','open','','295-revision','','','2008-08-20 13:05:08','2008-08-20 17:05:08','',295,'http://burningones.com/2008/08/20/295-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(297,2,'2008-09-03 17:44:14','2008-09-03 21:44:14','Outline:\nIntroduction\n\nThe effects of the Information Age\n---------------------------------\n\nIt\'s common knowledge.  We live in a time when the amount of information available to us has skyrocketed.  Our parents (or perhaps __you__) would go to libraries,subscribe to newspapers and magazines, listen to the radio, and watch TV if they wanted to be informed about current events and things they were interested in.  None of these options have disappeared and yet more have been added.  The advent of the Internet is over and it has entered into full-fledged membership in our society and culture.  We spend all day connected to it in one way or another.  Resources such as Google, Wikipedia, Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, and RSS Feeds have put new information at our finger tips at all times.  We can get Facebook updates sent our cell phones; We can update Twitter via text messaging; Almost anything can be researched fairly completely from Wikipedia, and the wealth of the entire Internet can be accessed quickly via Google.  This has created, in my perspective, a problem of \n\nGeneration-Y and Z\n------------------\n\nThe Attractiveness Of Information\n--------------------------------\n\nDefinition of Consumable Media\n    Consumable media is provided free of charge, interests you but is not required content for you to master, and comes in large volumes.  In addendum, it is more than likely archived and so can be recovered.  It is held in stark contrast to purchased, hard to replace media.\nTypes and Examples of Consumable Media\nIncorrect Media Associations\n    Magazines, Video Rentals, Libraries, Books, Etc.\nConclusion w/ reference to Part 2 of the 3 parter\n\nNotes:\n- Consumable Media is a first world problem because it arises when we seek to increase the amount of information at our fingertips.  The more information we try to consume, the harder it is for us to deal.','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'Media that costs nothing, is interesting but not necessary, and comes in large volumes is a first-world problem that has rapidly grown since the introduction of the internet.  I\'m proposing that a good title for this is Consumable Media and needs its own set of triage rules in order to deal with it (if you really want to deal with it at all).','inherit','open','open','','168-revision-4','','','2008-09-03 17:44:14','2008-09-03 21:44:14','',168,'http://burningones.com/2008/09/03/168-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(298,2,'2008-09-03 17:44:23','2008-09-03 21:44:23','Outline:\r\nIntroduction\r\n\r\nThe effects of the Information Age\r\n---------------------------------\r\n\r\nIt\'s common knowledge.  We live in a time when the amount of information available to us has skyrocketed.  Our parents (or perhaps __you__) would go to libraries,subscribe to newspapers and magazines, listen to the radio, and watch TV if they wanted to be informed about current events and things they were interested in.  None of these options have disappeared and yet more have been added.  The advent of the Internet is over and it has entered into full-fledged membership in our society and culture.  We spend all day connected to it in one way or another.  Resources such as Google, Wikipedia, Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, and RSS Feeds have put new information at our finger tips at all times.  We can get Facebook updates sent our cell phones; We can update Twitter via text messaging; Almost anything can be researched fairly completely from Wikipedia, and the wealth of the entire Internet can be accessed quickly via Google.  This has created, in my perspective, a problem.\r\n\r\nGeneration-Y and Z\r\n------------------\r\n\r\nThe Attractiveness Of Information\r\n--------------------------------\r\n\r\nDefinition of Consumable Media\r\n    Consumable media is provided free of charge, interests you but is not required content for you to master, and co