 of Consumable Media\r\nIncorrect Media Associations\r\n    Magazines, Video Rentals, Libraries, Books, Etc.\r\nConclusion w/ reference to Part 2 of the 3 parter\r\n\r\nNotes:\r\n- Consumable Media is a first world problem because it arises when we seek to increase the amount of information at our fingertips.  The more information we try to consume, the harder it is for us to deal.','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'Media that costs nothing, is interesting but not necessary, and comes in large volumes is a first-world problem that has rapidly grown since the introduction of the internet.  I\'m proposing that a good title for this is Consumable Media and needs its own set of triage rules in order to deal with it (if you really want to deal with it at all).','inherit','open','open','','168-revision-8','','','2008-09-03 17:47:57','2008-09-03 21:47:57','',168,'http://burningones.com/2008/09/03/168-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(302,2,'2008-09-03 17:55:31','2008-09-03 21:55:31','Outline:\nIntroduction\n\nThe Information Age\n-------------------\n\nIt\'s common knowledge.  We live in a time when the amount of information available to us has skyrocketed.  Our parents (or perhaps __you__) would go to libraries,subscribe to newspapers and magazines, listen to the radio, and watch TV if they wanted to be informed about current events and things they were interested in.  None of these options have disappeared and yet more have been added.  The advent of the Internet is over and it has entered into full-fledged membership in our society and culture.  We spend all day connected to it in one way or another.  Resources such as Google, Wikipedia, Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, and RSS Feeds have put new information at our finger tips at all times.  We can get Facebook updates sent our cell phones; We can update Twitter via text messaging; Almost anything can be researched fairly completely from Wikipedia; The wealth of the entire Internet can be accessed quickly via Google.  The predominant social expectation is one of being always on.  This has created, in my perspective, a problem.\n\nThe Attractiveness Of Information\n--------------------------------\nThe reason for this is fairly obvious.  Information is __really__ attractive.  Knowledge is power, right?  And now, the predominant technological developments of our time are all aiming to put more of that knowledge at our finger tips.  After all, when\'s the last time you bothered to create a list of Birthdays?  Facebook takes care of that for us.  When you\'re interested in what your friends have been up to, do you call them first or do you check their Facebook or Twitter statuses?  Do you run to a Library when you get interested in a subject or do you hit up Wikipedia or Google?  How often do you check your e-mail or IM status?  These are all technologies and services that have been developed very recently and yet they so attractively offer us information that they have become near irreversibly embedded into our social fabric.\n\nDefinition of Consumable Media\n    Consumable media is provided free of charge, interests you but is not required content for you to master, and comes in large volumes.  In addendum, it is more than likely archived and so can be recovered.  It is held in stark contrast to purchased, hard to replace media.\nTypes and Examples of Consumable Media\nIncorrect Media Associations\n    Magazines, Video Rentals, Libraries, Books, Etc.\nConclusion w/ reference to Part 2 of the 3 parter\n\nNotes:\n- Consumable Media is a first world problem because it arises when we seek to increase the amount of information at our fingertips.  The more information we try to consume, the harder it is for us to deal.','Perspectives on Consumable Media Part 1: What Is It?',0,'Media that costs nothing, is interesting but not necessary, and comes in large volumes is a first-world problem that has rapidly grown since the introduction of the internet.  I\'m proposing that a good title for this is Consumable Media and needs its own set of triage rules in order to deal with it (if you really want to deal with it at all).','inherit','open','open','','168-revision-9','','','2008-09-03 17:55:31','2008-09-03 21:55:31','',168,'http://burningones.com/2008/09/03/168-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0);
